      <h2>How Does an Ionizing Bar Work?</h2>
      <p>
        An ionizing bar uses <strong>corona discharge</strong>: high voltage (AC or DC, several kilovolts) is applied to an array of emitter needles. The electric field at each needle tip ionizes surrounding air molecules, creating positive and negative ions. These ions drift toward nearby charged surfaces and neutralize the static charge. The process is self-regulating — once the surface reaches neutral charge, ion absorption stops.
      </p>
      <p>
        Residual charge levels after treatment: typically <strong>±10–100V</strong> depending on bar type, working distance, and line speed.
      </p>

      <h3>Key Components of an Ionizer Bar</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Emitter needles</strong> — tungsten, stainless steel, or carbon-tipped pins that ionize the surrounding air</li>
        <li><strong>High-voltage power supply</strong> — generates the corona discharge voltage; AC or DC type</li>
        <li><strong>Grounded housing</strong> — shapes ion flow and protects personnel from high-voltage internals</li>
        <li><strong>Self-diagnostic system</strong> — on intelligent models, monitors ion balance and alerts when needles need cleaning</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Types of Ionizing Bars</h2>
      <p>The three main types differ in power supply, ion balance method, and performance level.</p>

      <h3>1. AC Ionizer Bars</h3>
      <p>
        AC ion bars produce both ion polarities from each needle simultaneously. They are simple, reliable, and cost-effective. Ion balance can drift as needles contaminate unevenly. Residual charge: <strong>±10–50V</strong>. Best for: packaging lines, general conveyors, cost-sensitive applications.
      </p>

      <h3>2. DC Pulsed Static Eliminators</h3>
      <p>
        DC pulsed units alternate positive and negative pulses with separate needle rows for each polarity. This enables precise ion balance adjustment. Residual charge: <strong>±5–20V</strong>. Self-diagnostic feedback is standard on most models. Best for: display panels, optical film lamination, high-speed lines.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Intelligent Anti-Static Bars</h3>
      <p>
        Intelligent static eliminators — such as the <a href="/products/static-eliminator/st-g-series">DGSDK ST-G Series</a> — combine DC pulsed ionization with real-time self-diagnostic monitoring. Built-in sensors detect needle contamination and ion imbalance before yield loss occurs. Best for: display manufacturing, semiconductor lines, critical production environments.
      </p>

      <h2>Ionizing Bar vs. Other Static Control Methods</h2>
