      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What is the difference between an ionizing bar and an ionizing blower?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">An ionizing bar covers a linear strip — it neutralizes static across the full width of a moving surface on a conveyor. An ionizing blower directs ion-laden airflow to a point or area and suits workbench applications. For production lines, the bar is the standard choice.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How close does an ionizing bar need to be to work?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Most ionization bars work at 25–150mm from the surface. Standard DC pulsed models achieve ±20–50V residual at 50–100mm. Long-range static eliminators (e.g., <a href="/products/static-eliminator/st-f-series">ST-F Series</a>) operate at up to 300–400mm.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Is a static elimination bar safe to touch?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">The ion cloud emitted from the unit is safe to touch. The housing is grounded and ion current at the surface is extremely low (microamps). Industrial static eliminators automatically disconnect high voltage if the housing is opened.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How do I know if my static eliminator is working?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Measure residual charge with a static field meter after the unit. A functioning static eliminator reduces charge to below ±100V for most applications, below ±20V for precision work. Intelligent models include built-in ion balance indicators.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What causes a static eliminator to fail?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Emitter needle contamination is the most common cause. Clean needles with a dry cotton swab to restore performance. Other causes include power supply failure, broken needles, and damaged housing. Intelligent models detect needle contamination automatically.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Can one ion rod cover the full width of my production line?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Standard ion rods reach up to 1,500mm and link end-to-end for wider applications. DGSDK produces static eliminators in custom lengths. <a href="/contact">Contact us</a> with your substrate width and line speed to confirm the right configuration.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

